<br>
That is why, when I played my cleric, I always tried to balance my mana with the group. If casters were spending a lot more than me, then I would encourage them to spend less or nuke once or twice myself to save them some mana and 'rebalance myself' with them. Then we could all med up together.<br>
<br>
When I play my wizard in melee groups, I similarly try to balance my mana with the healer's. Spending more mana against dangerous mobs or on multi-pulls, and less or even medding through single pulls. I view my role really as crowd control through damage(/stuns/snares/roots etc). Really though, my power is in soloing and ae groups.<br>
<br>
In my opinion, focus items are what is needed for balance at low and mid levels. Mudflation is impossible to prevent outside hard coded limits on items, which I think makes the game extremely stale and unfun (I didnt enjoy it in DAoC), so imho the best approach is to allow limited enjoyable mudflation but allow casters to 'inflate' at the same rate as melee (makes em sound like balloons <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
<br>
NToV, Primal loot etc increases melee damage and defense by huge amounts compared to, say, Seb loot (just look at Armok's tables) and Ancient spells are definitely needed to keep casters who go on the same raids up with the pace. Now guilds have a real solid reason to go kill one of these mobs to equip a caster, just like they did to equip a melee, and that has to be a good thing.<br>
<br>
